CRASH SUMMARY: On June 24, 2023, at approximately 0909 hours, Forestville Troopers were dispatched to the ramp from the I-495 Outer Loop to N/B Route 4 for a report of an overturned tractor and trailer with hazmat release. The weather was clear and visibility was unrestricted daylight conditions. Once the fireboard and the Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) declared the scene safe, I responded to conduct a post-crash inspection at the request of the Forestville Barrack. Upon arrival, I observed a 2017 Freightliner truck tractor bearing Ohio Registration PWV5257 attached to a 1999 Heil Cargo Tank Trailer bearing Indiana Registration P530053 resting on the right side. There was a large puddle of gasoline/water in the grassy area near the front of the trailer. base64," style="height:525px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> The tire marks on the roadway and the apparent skid marks across the grass area indicated that the CMV began to overturn while negotiating the downhill right curve on the exit ramp. The combination then overturned sliding on the left side of the CMV. When the truck approached the ramp from N/B Route 4 to the Outer Loop, it fully overturned, coming to final rest on the right side. base64," style="height:525px; margin:5px 10px; text-align:center; width:700px" /> The motor carrier was KAG Energy LLC dba Advantage Tank Lines (USDOT#469756) of North Canton, Ohio. The driver was Nigussie Hilemichael Tessema of Springfield, Virginia. Tessema was transported to Adventist Health Care Fort Washington Medical Center for non-life-threatening injuries prior to my arrival. The cargo tank was marked and placarded for UN1203 Gasoline, 3, II. The Hazmat Registration was observed and verified active through June 30, 2024. Brittany Westwood,[(240)704-2580] a company representative responded to the scene and provided Tessemas records of duty status, medical examiners certificate, and the bill of lading. The carrier arranged to have an empty tanker respond to the scene so that the contents of the overturned tanker could be transferred prior to attempting to upright the combination. After the cargo tank was emptied, Silverline towing responded to upright the combination. Once the vehicle was uprighted, I completed a Post Crash Inspection on the vehicle. base64," style="height:525px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:center"> margin-left:0; margin-right:0; margin-top:0; text-align:left"> B. INSPECTION RESULTS: Inspection report# MD0298004353 is attached. The only pre-collision defect observed was an out-of-adjustment brake on the trailer. The driver was cited for TA 21-801(b) Failure to control vehicle speed on highway to avoid collision. Defects that were a result of the crash were, 1 of 2 front clearance lights inoperative, damaged hubcap on axle 1 resulting in a lubricant leak, axle 1 left-front tire in contact with bumper, fuel tank securement violation, exhaust leak behind sleeper compartment, missing driver and passenger side rearview mirrors, left rear turn signal on trailer inoperative, and release of material from the package. base64," style="height:525px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" />
